    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Biotin for Hair Growth</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does biotin actually help hair grow?</summary>
      <p>Biotin (vitamin B7) is a coenzyme essential for keratin production — the structural protein that comprises 95% of hair. In biotin-deficient individuals, supplementation reliably reverses hair thinning and shedding. A 2015 study in <em>Skin Appendage Disorders</em> found that women with self-perceived thinning hair who took a biotin-containing supplement showed significant increases in hair growth and thickness after 90 days. However, most Americans already get adequate biotin from diet. The people most likely to benefit are those with genuine biotin insufficiency from frequent antibiotic use, pregnancy, or genetic biotinidase deficiency.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much biotin should I take daily for hair growth?</summary>
      <p>Most hair growth studies showing positive results used doses between 2,500mcg and 5,000mcg daily. Higher doses (10,000mcg) are available but have not demonstrated proportionally greater hair benefits in clinical research. Biotin is water-soluble, so excess is excreted rather than stored. The most important factor is consistent daily intake for a minimum of 90 days, as the hair growth cycle requires 3 to 6 months to show visible results from nutritional interventions.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How long does it take for biotin to help hair growth?</summary>
      <p>Expect a minimum of 90 days (3 months) before seeing visible improvements. Hair follicles cycle through growth, regression, and resting phases over 3 to 7 year periods. Biotin primarily affects new hair entering the growth phase, which takes at least one full cycle to become visible. Most clinical studies measure outcomes at the 90 to 180 day mark.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Does biotin cause acne or breakouts?</summary>
      <p>High-dose biotin (5,000mcg+) can cause acne in some individuals. The mechanism involves biotin competing with vitamin B5 for intestinal absorption. Since B5 regulates sebum production, high biotin can create a functional B5 deficiency leading to increased oil production and breakouts. If you experience acne, reduce to 2,500mcg and add a 500mg B5 supplement, or choose a product like Vegamour GRO that includes B5 in the formula.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can biotin interfere with lab tests?</summary>
      <p>Yes. The FDA issued a safety communication in 2017 warning that biotin supplementation can significantly interfere with thyroid panels, cardiac troponin tests, and some hormone assays. Discontinue biotin at least 48 to 72 hours before any blood draw and inform your healthcare provider about your biotin use.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Is biotin better than collagen for hair growth?</summary>
      <p>Biotin and collagen support hair through different mechanisms. Biotin is the coenzyme required for keratin synthesis; collagen provides amino acid building blocks (proline, glycine) for keratin assembly and supports the dermal layer around follicles. For best results, many dermatologists recommend combining both. Products like Sports Research Biotin + Keratin address both pathways simultaneously.</p>
    </details>

